    "body": "### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.5.0\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nCentOS\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nWezterm 20210814-124438-54e29167\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\ntmux-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nNix (using the unstable branch to get 0.5.0)\r\n\r\n### How to reproduce the issue\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim -u NONE\r\n:set sw=4\r\niabc def<esc>        # insert `abc def`\r\n^                    # move cursor away\r\n>>                   # indent\r\ngi                   # try to get to the last insert location\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nLast insert location should use an extmark, to follow line changes like an indentation.\r\n\r\nAfter the `gi` command, I'd expect the cursor to go back after `def|`\r\n\r\n### Actual behavior\r\n\r\nLast insert location seems to be stored as a row/col, and `gi` moves the cursor after `abc|`",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Last insert location [is a mark](https://github.com/muniter/neovim/blob/5fd21b8d3e9dcb2b3dc3bdab4b58218ac908e3e8/src/nvim/mark.c#L341) and as such [tracks a position](https://github.com/muniter/neovim/blob/5fd21b8d3e9dcb2b3dc3bdab4b58218ac908e3e8/src/nvim/mark.c#L974). but is not an extmark like any other normal mark. Extmarks arguably have better tracking of text changes.\r\n\r\nSo this is not actually an issue, rather that normal marks are not that good?",
